			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I looked at my APU doc and found clarification.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">----------<br />Sweep Unit<br />----------<br /><br />The sweep unit can adjust a square channel's period periodically. It contains a<br />divider and a shifter.<br /><br />A channel's second register configures the sweep unit:<br /><br />    eppp nsss       enable, period, negate, shift<br /><br />The divider's period is set to p + 1.<br /><br />The shifter continuously calculates a result based on the channel's period. The<br />channel's period (from the third and fourth registers) is first shifted right<br />by s bits. If negate is set, the shifted value's bits are inverted, and on the<br />second square channel, the inverted value is incremented by 1. The resulting<br />value is added with the channel's current period, yielding the final result.<br /><br />When the sweep unit is clocked, the divider is *first* clocked and then if<br />there was a write to the sweep register since the last sweep clock, the divider<br />is reset.<br /><br />When the channel's period is less than 8 or the result of the shifter is<br />greater than $7FF, the channel's DAC receives 0 and the sweep unit doesn't<br />change the channel's period. Otherwise, if the sweep unit is enabled and the<br />shift count is greater than 0, when the divider outputs a clock, the channel's<br />period in the third and fourth registers are updated with the result of the<br />shifter.</div><br />The style of writing I used in the APU doc is to minimize implied things or redundancy. Above it says that if <s>result</s> <strong>raw period</strong> &lt; 8 or result &gt; $7FF, the DAC receives 0, and the sweep unit won't change the channel's period. Otherwise... (i.e. the rest of the paragraph is void <em>unless</em> <s>result</s> <strong>raw period</strong> &gt;= 8 and result &lt;= $7FF).<br /><br />I can verify this next time I've got my NES RE machine on, so you can update the Wiki.<br /><br />I intended for the APU reference pages on the Wiki to contain just a concise but complete description of APU operation, without <em>any</em> practical usage notes, not even &quot;this means that ...&quot; (since such statements are a kludge when the description could be made clearer and not need a clarifying comment). I think that mixing it all together leads to a more watered-down language that leaves unanswered questions.<br /><br />EDIT: fixed error in my paraphrasing of the quoted doc.</div>

					
							<br /><br />
