						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Above it says that if result &lt; 8 or result &gt; $7FF, the DAC receives 0, and the sweep unit won't change the channel's period.</div><br /><br />It doesn't say &quot;result &lt; 8&quot; though, but &quot;current period &lt; 8&quot;. If the current period is &gt;=8 and the result would be &lt;8, then &quot;when the channel's period is less than 8 [...] the sweep unit doesn't change the channel's period&quot; implies that the period would be changed by the sweep unit, while &quot;result &lt; 8&quot; implies that it wouldn't be changed. So which one is it?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I intended for the APU reference pages on the Wiki to contain just a concise but complete description of APU operation, without <em>any</em> practical usage notes, not even &quot;this means that ...&quot; (since such statements are a kludge when the description could be made clearer and not need a clarifying comment). I think that mixing it all together leads to a more watered-down language that leaves unanswered questions.</div><br /><br />I mostly agree with this.</div>

