			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">So $4015 writes set an enabled flag (basically, it remembers the last write to $4015). I take it that writing 0 clears the active flag, but writing 1 doesn't affect the active flag. And then, writing the third channel register when the enabled flag is set sets the active flag, the length counter is only clocked when the active flag is set, and the length counter reaching 0 clears the active flag (really, it probably loads the counter with one less than the count, so that it wrapping around is it &quot;reaching 0&quot;, so it's just the carry out the top that clears the active flag). I suppose this makes sense from a hardware view, rather than having to check whether the length counter is 0 on a $4015 read etc.<br /><br />This kind of thing makes sense in a description of the hardware implementation, since it's important for understanding the schematic, but from a behavior POV, it just adds complication. I'm torn though because claiming that writing to $4015 can clear a length counter to 0 is an outright lie. Essentially the abstract description becomes a micro-optimization of things to reduce the number of variables in the abstract model.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
